# Node / TypeScript Services — Clean Architecture Guidelines

When adding or editing code in backend apps under `apps/<app-name>/`, follow clean architecture and the structure below. Prefer one app as the **reference** for REST (and gRPC when present) and keep new endpoints consistent with that app.

## 1. Folder structure

```
apps/<app-name>/src/
  main.ts                           # Entry: load config, wire dependencies, start HTTP or gRPC server
  application/
    ports/                          # Outbound interfaces (repository, storage, publisher, etc.)
    services/                       # Application services / use-cases (depend on ports, use domain)
  domain/
    entities/                       # Domain entities (types, factories; no framework or I/O imports)
  adapters/
    http/                           # HTTP transport: controller + routes
      <feature>_controller.ts
      routes/
        <feature>_routes.ts
    grpc/                           # gRPC transport: server implementation (controller), optional
      <feature>_controller.ts
    postgres/                       # SQL persistence: implements repository ports
    object-storage/                 # S3/MinIO: implements file-storage port
    rabbitmq/                       # Messaging: implements publisher port
```

- **Entry** (`main.ts`): Load config (env or validated config module), build adapters → inject into application services → inject services into HTTP/gRPC controllers, register routes, start servers. No business logic in `main`.
- **Application**: Ports (interfaces) and services (use-cases) live under `application/`. Services depend only on ports and domain entities.
- **Adapters**: All transport and persistence live under `adapters/`, grouped by technology (`http`, `grpc`, `postgres`, `object-storage`, `rabbitmq`). HTTP and gRPC adapters are thin: parse request, call service, format response.

Shared cross-app code, when needed, belongs in workspace libraries (e.g. `libs/<lib-name>/src/`) instead of duplicating under each app.

## 2. Domain entities

- Place under `domain/entities/`; one module per entity (e.g. `video.ts`, `short-link.ts`).
- **Types** with explicit fields; use **factory functions** (or small classes) for new aggregates and keep status/const enums or union types in the same module.
- **Factory**: `function createVideo(input: CreateVideoInput): Video` (or `export class Video { static create(...) }`) for new aggregates (set ID, timestamps, default status). Validate use-case rules in the application service or at the transport edge when appropriate.
- No dependency on HTTP frameworks, DB drivers, or gRPC generated code. Domain may depend only on Node builtins, small pure utilities, or **shared libs** that stay free of I/O.
- Prefer **named exports** for types, factories, and status constants.

```ts
// domain/entities/video.ts
export const VideoStatus = {
  Processing: 'processing',
  Ready: 'ready',
} as const;
export type VideoStatus = (typeof VideoStatus)[keyof typeof VideoStatus];

export type Video = {
  id: string;
  userId: string;
  title: string;
  status: VideoStatus;
  createdAt: Date;
  updatedAt: Date;
};

export function createVideo(userId: string, title: string): Video {
  const now = new Date();
  return {
    id: crypto.randomUUID(),
    userId,
    title,
    status: VideoStatus.Processing,
    createdAt: now,
    updatedAt: now,
  };
}
```

## 3. Ports (outbound interfaces)

- Place under `application/ports/`; one module per concern (e.g. `video_repository.ts`, `file_storage_repository.ts`, `upload_process_publisher.ts`).
- **Interfaces** only; methods take/return **domain entities** (from `domain/entities`) or primitives. Use `import type` where it helps avoid circular runtime imports.
- Name by role: `VideoRepository`, `FileStorageRepository`, `UploadProcessPublisher`. Suffix with the role (`Repository`, `Publisher`, etc.).
- Ports are implemented by adapters under `adapters/` (`postgres`, `object-storage`, `rabbitmq`, etc.).

```ts
// application/ports/video_repository.ts
import type { Video } from '../../domain/entities/video';

export interface VideoRepository {
  create(video: Video): Promise<void>;
  getById(id: string): Promise<Video | null>;
  update(video: Video): Promise<void>;
}
```

## 4. Application services

- One module (or one per bounded context) under `application/services/` (e.g. `upload_service.ts`).
- **Constructor** or factory receives **port interfaces** (repositories, storage, publisher), not concrete adapter classes.
- Methods: create/load entities, call ports; return domain data or throw **typed / discriminated errors** the transport layer can map. Prefer `Error` subclasses or a small `Result` type only if the codebase already uses that pattern consistently.
- Validation that is use-case specific (e.g. allowed file extensions) can live in the service; keep domain free of I/O.
- No HTTP, gRPC, or database driver types; only domain entities, ports, and shared pure utilities.

```ts
// application/services/upload_service.ts
import type { VideoRepository } from '../ports/video_repository';
import type { UploadRepository } from '../ports/upload_repository';
import { createVideo } from '../../domain/entities/video';

export class UploadService {
  constructor(
    private readonly videoRepo: VideoRepository,
    private readonly uploadRepo: UploadRepository,
  ) {}

  async requestPresignUrl(userId: string, title: string): Promise<{ videoId: string; url: string }> {
    const video = createVideo(userId, title);
    await this.videoRepo.create(video);
    // ...
    return { videoId: video.id, url: '...' };
  }
}
```

## 5. Controllers and routes (adapters)

- **HTTP**: Under `adapters/http/`; `<feature>_controller.ts`. Constructor or factory receives the **service**. Parse/validate request (schema validation at the edge), call service, set status and JSON body. Routes live under `adapters/http/routes/` (e.g. `<feature>_routes.ts`) and export a function such as `registerUploadRoutes(app: Express, c: UploadController)` or the equivalent for your framework.
- **gRPC**: Under `adapters/grpc/`; implement the generated service interface. Constructor receives the **service**. In each RPC: validate request, call service method, map to the response type.
- **Errors**: Map service errors to HTTP status codes (404, 400, 500) or gRPC status codes. Do not leak stack traces or internal messages in response bodies in production.
- Controllers are thin adapters: no business rules, only translation between transport DTOs and service calls.

## 6. Adapters (persistence and messaging)

- **Postgres**: Under `adapters/postgres/`; one module per repository. Implements `VideoRepository`, `UploadRepository`, etc. Constructor receives a pool/client (e.g. `pg.Pool`). Map rows to/from `domain/entities` types; use `null`/`undefined` consistently for optional fields.
- **Object storage**: Under `adapters/object-storage/`; modules implementing `FileStorageRepository`. Keep SDK types inside the adapter.
- **Messaging**: Under `adapters/rabbitmq/` (or similar); implements `UploadProcessPublisher`. Isolate connection/channel lifecycle here.
- Group by technology; `main.ts` wires concrete adapters and passes interfaces into the service.

## 7. Entry and wiring (`main.ts`)

- **Config**: Read from `process.env` or a small validated config module (e.g. schema with Zod/Valibot if the project already uses one). Fail fast on missing required values.
- **Wire**: Instantiate adapters (postgres repos, object-storage, rabbitmq publisher), then construct the service with port types, then HTTP controller and gRPC controller with the service. Call route registration functions. Register gRPC service implementation on the gRPC server.
- **Server**: Create the HTTP app and/or gRPC server, register routes and services, then listen. Keep `main.ts` short; no business logic.

## 8. Naming and modules

- **Entities**: `Video`, `ShortLink` in `domain/entities/` as types + factories.
- **Ports**: `VideoRepository`, `FileStorageRepository` in `application/ports/` as `interface` (or `type` aliases to interfaces).
- **Service**: `UploadService` in `application/services/` as a class or explicit module with exported functions.
- **HTTP**: Controller and routes in `adapters/http/` and `adapters/http/routes/`.
- **gRPC**: Controller in `adapters/grpc/`; avoid naming files or imports that shadow the `@grpc/grpc-js` package.
- **Adapters**: Implementation modules export factories like `createVideoRepository(pool: Pool): VideoRepository`.

## 9. Shared code (`libs/` or `packages/`)

Use workspace libraries for code reused across apps:

- **Config**: Shared env loading and validation.
- **Logger**: Structured logging for adapters and controllers; avoid logging inside domain or application services unless diagnosing clearly optional diagnostics.
- **Util**: Small pure helpers (e.g. normalization, ID helpers) usable from domain or adapters.
- **Messaging / DB clients**: Connection helpers; service-specific behavior stays in each app’s ports and adapters.
- **Middleware**: HTTP middleware (auth, logging, recovery); gRPC interceptors if shared.

Prefer **domain per app** in `apps/<app-name>/src/domain/`. Put DTOs in `libs/` only when truly shared across services; avoid a single mega-shared “models” package that becomes an accidental coupled layer.

## 10. Adding a new aggregate or capability

1. Add entity in `domain/entities/` with type(s) and factory.
2. Add or extend a port in `application/ports/` (e.g. `XRepository`).
3. Add or extend a service in `application/services/` that depends on the new port and entities.
4. Add or extend HTTP controller in `adapters/http/` and route registration in `adapters/http/routes/`, and/or gRPC controller in `adapters/grpc/`.
5. Add or extend adapter in `adapters/postgres/`, `object-storage/`, `rabbitmq/` (or a new folder) implementing the port.
6. In `main.ts`: instantiate the new adapter, inject into the service, inject service into controller(s), register routes/gRPC, start servers.

## 11. Comments

- Do **not** add comments in code unless they are required for **OpenAPI** tooling (e.g. JSDoc consumed by `swagger-jsdoc` / tsoa / Fastify schema metadata).
- Prefer clear names and small functions over explanatory comments. If something needs a comment to be understood, consider refactoring instead.
